natural problem: Let $f(x) = ax^7 + bx^3 + cx - 5.$  If $f(-7) = 7,$ then find $f(7).$

a_0.formal problem:
theorem
fixes a b c x :: real and f :: "real \<Rightarrow> real"
assumes h0 : "\<forall> x. f x = a * x powr 7 + b * x powr 3 + c * x - 5"
and h1 : "f (-7) = 7"
shows  "f 7 = -17"
a_0.formal solution:
(* ### Problem
 Let $f(x) = ax^7 + bx^3 + cx - 5.$  If $f(-7) = 7,$ then find $f(7).$ The final Answer is -17
 ### Proof
 Note that \begin{align} f(x) + f(-x) &= (ax^7 + bx^3 + cx - 5) + (a(-x)^7 + b(-x)^3 + c(-x) - 5) \\ &= (ax^7 + bx^3 + cx - 5) + (-ax^7 - bx^3 - cx - 5) \\ &= -10. \end{align}In particular, $f(7) + f(-7) = -10,$ so $f(7) = -10 - f(-7) = \boxed{-17}.$
 *)
